American journalist Jill Carroll, a freelancer for The Christian Science Monitor, was kidnapped in Iraq while on assignment.
Her Iraqi interpreter was killed during the abduction.
The Monitor called for her release, highlighting her work in revealing the truth about the Iraq war.
Carroll's family issued an emotional plea for her safe return, emphasizing her dedication to the Iraqi people.
The US government denied negotiating with insurgents in Iraq, while Carroll's captors threatened her with execution unless female prisoners were freed.
The situation remains tense as efforts continue to secure Carroll's release.
